    <div class="w3-container">
      <h3><b>BORIS BLAMES ‘THE HERD’ FOR RESIGNATION. HAS HE FORGOTTEN PARTYGATE, PATERSON, AND PINCHER? </b></h3>
      <h5>Boris Johnson has officially resigned as the leader of the Conservative party, much to the relief of several prominent members of the party, and is expected to serve as Prime Minister until a new party leader is elected in autumn, <span> <b> Adam Havis 9B</b></span></h5>
    </div>

    <div class="w3-container">
      <p>On Thursday 7th July, Boris Johnson spoke outside of 10 Downing Street to a crowd of spectators, announcing his decision to resign in the face of unprecedented mass resignations by top members of his government. </p>

<p>Just two days previously, his Health Secretary Sajid Javid and Chancellor Rishi Sunak had quit, after seeing Johnson’s appalling handling of sexual misconduct allegations against Chris Pincher. Mr Sunak stated in a letter that he "rightly expects government to be conducted properly, competently and seriously".</p>  

<p>This caused a cascade of resignations and letters of no confidence to pour in from other ministers, with many senior conservatives urging Mr Johnson himself to resign. However, the Prime Minister clung onto power, claiming that he would not give up his "colossal mandate" from the 2019 election. </p>

<p>By Thursday, more than 50 ministers had resigned, including Education Secretary Michelle Donelan, who had been appointed less than two days ago, and the government could not perform its role due to lack to staff. </p>

<p>Finally, at midday, standing at his podium, Boris Johnson resigned with a speech in which he appeared to regret nothing, clearly believing that he still has a right to remain as Prime Minister.</p> 

<p>In his speech, Mr Johnson made no mention of his previous scandals, such as his major breach of lockdown regulations, or his appointment of Chris Pincher, despite knowing of allegations of sexual misconduct against him. Instead, he blamed his own party for his downfall, comparing them to stampeding animals. “As we have seen at Westminster … when the herd moves, it moves.”, Johnson said. Nor did he express any interest in apologising, or even thanking his fellow ministers who had defended him in parliament.</p>  

<p>It is expected that while a leadership battle rages on in the conservative party, Johnson will act as “care-taker” for the nation, but even this decision is also under heavy criticism. Many leading members of parliament want Boris out of office as soon as possible, with some calling for Theresa May to return and take the role of “care-taker”. 

<p>Top contenders for the new leader of the conservatives include Rishi Sunak, the former Chancellor who became a household name after his series of plans to kick-start the economy after covid; Penny Mordaunt, the international trade minister who hasn’t been afraid to criticise Boris Johnson; and Sajid Javid, the former health secretary with a focus on integrity.</p>  

<p>Meanwhile, elsewhere in the world, there is little support for Mr Johnson. Many EU member states shared a dislike of the Prime Minister after Brexit, and they haven’t warmed up to him since. The French finance minister Bruno Le Maire has said that: “personally, I won’t miss him”, and Guy Verhofstadt, a Belgian politician, claimed that “Boris Johnson’s reign ends in disgrace”. </p> 

<p>Similarly, Joe Biden in the United States seems ready to move on, as evidence by his recent speech concerning Anglo-American relations, where he didn’t even mention Boris Johnson by name. In Russia, Vladimir Putin’s spokesman Dmitry Peskov stated that Johnson “really does not like us – and we [do not like] him either”.   </p>

<p>It seems that after long 3 years of scandals and broken promises, the Boris Johnson era has at last drawn to a close. Only one question remains unanswered. Who will succeed him? </p>
      <div class="w3-row">
        <div class="w3-col m8 s12">
		</p>
          <p><b><a class="w3-button w3-padding-large w3-white w3-border" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/boris-johnson-prime-minister-resigns-uk-government-11657144874?mod=world_major_2_pos3" target="_blank">READ OTHER ARTICLES>></b></a>
        </div>
