    <div class="w3-container">
      <h3><b>Why America allowing abortion laws to be left to the States is an injurious idea  </b></h3>
      <h5>On 24th June 2022, the US Supreme Court overturned Roe v Wade – an historic case which legalised abortion across the nation.   <span> <b> Aaron Brainch 9B</b></span></h5>
    </div>

    <div class="w3-container">
      <p>Roe v Wade began in 1969 when Norma McCorvey (known by her legal pseudonym “Jane Roe”) became pregnant and wished to seek an abortion. However, her state (Texas) and made abortion illegal unless it was to save the mother’s life. Roe and her lawyers went up against the local district attorney Henry Wade and won the case on the grounds that this abortion law was a violation of her constitutional rights. On 22nd January 1973, the US Supreme Court described a right to abortion as “fundamental” which challenged many abortion laws in a number of states. 

<p>The reasoning behind the overturning of this case was due to the fact that the arguments presented were “exceptionally weak” and were “egregiously wrong” according to Justice Samuel Alito who wrote on behalf of the court majority.  

<p>As of the 8th July 2022, according to the Guttmacher Institute, 25 out of 50 or 50% of states in the USA have been labelled as being “restrictive”, “very restrictive”, or “most restrictive” in terms of abortion laws which will have the potential to effect 40 million women of child-bearing age in the USA.   

<p>However, the decision to grant states the ability to make their own abortion laws will soon reveal itself as prodigious error that will inflict more harm than good in a plethora of ways. These include the fact that dangerous abortions will still be carried out, a rise of children needing adoption will occur (which is not a perfect system to begin with), some people cannot afford children and this outcome will punish victims of rape instead of the perpetrators.  

<p>In spite of the decision to ban or heavily restrict abortions in some states, people residing in them will still perform them regardless. However, as possibilities of doing so begin to dwindle, these people will be forced to use unsafe methods and will end up severely harming themselves. This is not simply speculation. In the times before Roe v Wade occurred, some people resorted to using coat hangers, broken bottles, hooks and needles to perform self-induced abortions. Everyday items were used out of frenetic desperation to perform abortions so women could be liberated and free of a responsibility they could not handle. This resulted in a series of women becoming infected with diseases from unsterilised items, puncturing their uteruses and losing lots of blood and in extreme cases, losing their lives. If actions are not taken to reverse this overturn, women in states with restrictive abortion laws will become forced endure multitudes of risk and pain all because they were denied freedom to their own body. The same freedom the United States of America have proudly boasted for decades.  

<p>In addition to unsafe abortions occurring, those who are forced to carry a baby to term may not have the resources available to successfully take care of a baby and provide it with a loving life. Even before the baby is taken out of the hospital, mothers can face a bill of over $13,000 and in some cases, a bill of $20,000-$30,000. Although some of this will be paid by medical insurance, the mother will still be expected to cover part of it which may result in them paying thousands of dollars anyway. This year, the average cost of raising a child to 18 is estimated to be $272,049 which many people, particularly those in poverty, cannot afford. Aside from the financial perspective, some women, who have been denied abortions and forced to carry a baby term, simply do not have enough time to raise a child. In the long run, this will lead to neglect and would cause a large number of children to fall astray due to problems regarding brain development according to the NSPCC. In the event of teenage pregnancies, young parents will most likely not be able to take care of a baby which will severely impact their social lives, stifle their academic progress and deteriorate their own mental wellbeing. 1 in 10 abortions are performed on teenagers meaning the banning of abortions will only cause these issues to exacerbate.  

<p>Text BoxAs well as some people not being able to afford children, the overturn of Roe v Wade will cause there to be an extreme increase in the number of children needing adoption. When women begin to birth unwanted infants, not all of them will find themselves in the same household as their mothers. Therefore, these babies will be crammed into the adoption system which although works in the US now, will not be able to handle the sheer influx of children in the near future. This will lead to some children never being adopted and being catapulted into a world they have little idea of how to navigate. In the US, adoptions rates are already declining as in 2019, 115,353 children were adopted whereas in 2020, that number fell to 95,306. In extreme cases, some unfortunate women may resort to simply abandoning their babies.   

<p>The illegalisation and restriction of abortions also punishes victims of rape with the burden of an unwanted child giving them a permanent reminder of a forlorn and scarring incident. A situation similar to this almost occurred this month in July 2022 when a 10-year-old girl and victim of rape was denied an abortion in Ohio as according to Ohio’s laws, she had been pregnant for too long (a mere six weeks and three days). She was forced to travel to out of state to Indiana where she could receive an abortion. Incidents like this will only become more common with the overturn of Roe v Wade and states having the power to determine abortion laws is criminal. Denying a minor, a girl who had only lived one decade of life and a victim of rape an abortion is an infringement of her personal freedom and liberty.  

<p>Overall, allowing abortion laws to be left to the states is an injurious idea as dangerous abortions will still be carried out, a rise of children needing adoption will occur, not all infants will be cared for and victims of rape will be unjustly punished for something out of their control. The banning and restriction of abortion is a malignant attack, is unconstitutional and limits the power of an individual over their own body.   </p>
      <div class="w3-row">
        <div class="w3-col m8 s12">
		</p>
          <p><b><a class="w3-button w3-padding-large w3-white w3-border" href="
https://www.politico.com/news/2022/05/02/supreme-court-abortion-draft-opinion-00029473" target="_blank">READ OTHER ARTICLES>></b></a>
        </div>
        <div class="w3-col m4 w3-hide-small">          
