    <div class="w3-container">
      <h3><b>WAR IN UKRAINE: A RUSSIAN FAILURE ON THE BATTLEFIELD AND IN THE MEDIA  </b></h3>
      <h5>Ukraine has defied all expectations of being overrun and defeated within months, partially due to the huge amount of Western aid and to the strategic failures of the Kremlin. Ukraine may not be winning every battle on the frontline but is winning in the information war.  <span> <b> Matthew Wang 9B</b></span></h5>
    </div>

    <div class="w3-container">
      <p>Since the start of Putin’s ‘special military operation’ in late February this year, which was a war that the Kremlin believed would end in a quick and decisive Russian victory. Raging on for nearly 5 months, it is clear this conflict would have no quick end, fuelled by the will to fight and defend their homeland of the Ukrainians and the endless attacks by Russian forces, this far in, Putin can no longer afford to lose this conflict, Russian forces have suffered losses and committed resources to a point where it has become better to continue the war in hopes of victory than to retreat and pull out of Ukraine, which would not only be a tremendous waste in resources and destabilise Putin’s regime, but also it would show the world to a greater extent how the current Russian armed forces has only a fraction of the power to the previous Soviet Red Army, causing internal and international humiliation and an economy in ruins. 

<p>To avoid a deadly confrontation with Russia, the West, NATO, have resorted to sending defensive munitions and weaponry to Ukraine to stem the Russian invasion. It must be said that NATO’s defensive weaponry have had a profound effect in the defence of Ukraine, and such modern technology such as the FGM-148 Javelin anti-tank guided missile, have facilitated the destruction of tanks and armoured vehicles, in addition to MANPADS, man-portable air-defence system, just to name a few. Western aid to Ukraine has been massive, with NATO members such as the UK providing £2.3 billion in military aid to Ukraine and $4.6 billion from the US, with Congress approving an enormous aid package of nearly $40 billion. The aid package includes $3.9 billion to support U.S. forces stationed in Europe and $19 billion for immediate military assistance to Ukraine, continuing the effort that has been essential to maintaining Ukrainian resistance. Along with $2 billion for long-term support for NATO partners and DOD modernization projects, the package also includes nearly $16 billion for economic assistance to Ukraine, worldwide humanitarian relief, and a range of multinational programmes. However, much of the military equipment donated to Ukraine has been taken from a wide variety of Western weapon stocks, donating equipment is all good and well, however the problem is “the ability of the Ukrainians to absorb all of this equipment” as stated by Mark Cancian, a senior advisor with the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) Security Program. Ukrainian forces have previously been trained on Soviet-era weapons left over after the fall of the USSR in 1991, now they are trying to switch over to newer and more modernised Western systems which may take weeks or even months to train crews to operate. Mark Cancian has also stated that NATO countries, by sending equipment, which are of different systems, have exacerbated the situation. Ukrainian forces now must be trained to use two different systems, as well as creating separate supply chains for spare parts. Even with these complexities, it is almost certain that without the vast amounts of Western aid, Kyiv would have certainly fallen to Putin’s forces by now. 

<p>The defence of Ukraine has been somewhat helped by the numerous and significant challenges to logistics and supply chains, as well as poor planning of Russian forces, and the Kremlin underestimating the willpower of the Ukrainian people in addition to misjudging the international response. Putin somewhat stubbornly believed that many Ukrainians would support the annexation by Russia.  

<p>Putin’s speech was poorly composed and lacked any sort of reasonable justification which would rally support. By claiming the “de-Nazification” of Ukraine, it became clear that someone in the Kremlin did not perform the basic task of research, and the reason became widely disregarded as the elected President of Ukraine, Volodymyr Zelenskyy, was himself Jewish. Ukraine also has the third largest Jewish population in Europe and has laws condemning Nazi and Communist totalitarian regimes and banning the spread and use of their symbols and the public denial of their crimes. This immediately made Putin lose credibility and hence lost much of the already thin support for the war. 

<p>Wars are also won by the ability to hold the land and control the population living in that area. This has proved difficult for the Russian forces, as it has become evident that much of the Ukrainian population is hostile towards the invading army. The war, for some Ukrainians, has turned into a patriotic war, with many people volunteering to fight. Problems arise in urban combat, where with modern social media and the internet, it has become easier for defending forces to know the locations of opponents, which has been seen when Ukrainian residents have posted videos of Russian units moving in their area. This gives significant advantage to the Ukrainian military in defence of strategic urban areas. However, this also blurs the line between the non-combatant and the combatant, as civilians who use any devices to share information which helps the Ukrainian forces, can be considered as part of a military element.  

<p>Russian ground forces began with quick territorial gains on the Northern Front, helped by the superior numbers of artillery and mechanised formations. This advance was short lived after suffering serious casualties due to Ukrainian ambushes against tanks and other armoured vehicles, helped by the donations of NLAWs (Next generation Light Anti-tank Weapon) by Western countries such as the UK which had donated 5000 of those systems. The majority of Russian ground units were battalion tactical groups, which were combined arms formations which were in theory meant to be self-sufficient, but in practise were not operating at maximum strength and lacked infantry support. 

<p>Logistical and maintenance issues were widespread, especially in areas of combat and active fighting. Faster formations were able to push forward quickly, and out of the reach of support companies which left them with limited capability to continue advancing or hold ground. Putin’s forces also failed to provide sufficient convoy protection, often leading to vehicles on the frontline being abandoned after breaking down due to a lack of engineers, parts and recovery vehicles.  

<p>Ukraine has shown the utility of UAVs (unmanned aerial vehicles) in combat, by coordination with Ukrainian ground units and special forces to locate and destroy targets and formations with high accuracy. With the help of the UAVs, Ukrainian forces have also managed to sink the Russian Black Sea Fleet flagship Moskva.  

<p>The Russian advance has not been helped by the failure of the Russian air force to gain aerial superiority in Ukraine, even though they have conducted missile strikes against key military infrastructure which included air defences. Equipment such as the FGM-92 Stinger system, which is easily operated, man portable, and available in large numbers through Western aid.  

<p>On the other hand, Russian forces have had success in the Donbas region of Eastern Ukraine. This has been due to the enormous artillery firepower the Russian army possesses, which have been able to effectively support infantry and formations on the frontline, sometimes making up for the sub-par quality of Putin’s ground forces. 

<p>Russia themselves also have utilised UAVs in the conflict in Ukraine, however, have suffered losses to electronic jamming systems or have been simply shot down. This places Russia in a bad place as the Russia lacks the industry and technology to replace these lost drones. It is a similar story is many other highly advanced equipment Russia fields. Many of them require parts which require skilled manufacturing and advanced industry of which some parts have been made in countries such as the UK and the USA. 

<p>On the information front, Ukraine seems to have the support of many nations and people. Zelenskyy is a key player in their campaign to appeal to foreign, mainly Western and NATO, governments to secure military and economic aid. He also received a standing ovation from the House of Commons and EU Parliament. The use of social media has shown to have great influence on the opinions of many people in foreign countries. 

<p>The Ukrainian forces have much high morale than the Russian troops, and this plays a key part in the continuation of the war. It is much likely for Russian forces to be exhausted and to lack motivation than the defending Ukrainian army.  

<p>Videos and pictures of Ukrainians in defiance against their Russian occupiers have been hugely successful in gaining approval and spreading the information of the war. However, it must be said that there have also been misleading posts, which have turned out to be false, a note to take that all sides have propaganda and campaigns to influence public opinion. 

<p>Public opinion in Western countries have also shown to influence the actions of those countries’ leaders, notably PM of the UK, Boris Johnson, who has sent vast stockpiles of British army equipment to Ukraine, in an effort to distract from internal issues regarding his premiership.  

<p>Along with this, the war invited overwhelming international condemnation of Russia, of 193 nations: 141 countries voted in support of the condemnation of Russia, while only 5: Belarus, Syria, North Korea, Eritrea and Russia voted against. Even countries usually friendly to Russia, mainly China, abstained from voting, making mockery of the “no limits” friendship statement between Moscow and Beijing just weeks prior. 

<p>Even though it seems that Ukraine is currently able to hold and keep Putin’s army at bay, and maintain extensive international and internal support, there will come a point where even with the military equipment donated by the West, the Ukrainian forces will start to lose grip and their defences will slowly weaken. The Russian forces have already changed strategy of holding territories that they have gained, and advance by attacking small targets on the frontline. With greater stockpiles of artillery shells, Putin’s army can sustain artillery bombardment for much longer and hit Ukrainian forces behind the frontline.  

<p>If Ukraine is to win the war against tyranny, the West must coordinate and communicate better with Ukraine in order to provide the munitions and equipment necessary to continue the fight, however NATO must tread with caution. As we have seen, Putin’s behaviour is erratic, and the West must be sure to not push him over to edge to nuclear escalation which will lead to mutually assured destruction.  </p>
      <div class="w3-row">
        <div class="w3-col m8 s12">
		</p>
