<div class="w3-card-4 w3-margin w3-white">
    <div class="w3-container">
      <h3><b>Is our rail industry going off the rails? </b></h3>
      <h5>It's no secret that Britain’s rail industry is in a state of disarray, but what really are the problems, and why is the railway so bad?<span><b>Alfie Marjoram 9B</b></span></h5>
    </div>

    <div class="w3-container">
      <p>
	  In the first three months of this year, the Office of Rail and Road reports that 72.4 percent of trains ran on-time. As such, if you travel to work by train, five days a week, then you are likely to be delayed on three of your journeys. The report also shows that 3.9 percent of trains were cancelled, which means that, in one month of travelling to work, at least one of your trains will not operate. 

 

<p>The above statistics only hold true if the trains are actually running. Just last month, there was an entire week of major travel disruption as members of the RMT Union went on strike across the country because of disputes over pay. The strikes meant that 80 percent of trains were cancelled, and millions of people were unable to get to work. Mick Lynch, senior member of the Union, says that passengers ‘should be prepared for rail strikes to continue well into the autumn.’ 

 

<p>Unfortunately, the government is not doing much to help the industry. On 27th of June 2022, Transport for London received its fifth 'extended budget,’ worth £200 million, which ends today. As with many issues, the dispute is a matter of politics: a Conservative government disputing with the Labour Mayor of London. Yet, the government is still not providing what the company is pleading for: a long-term funding agreement. ‘We think that cutting services should be your last resort, not your first… TfL services are not at risk unless you want them to be’ says Grant Shapps, Transport Secretary for England. Despite these promises, the services are still at a huge risk if funding isn't provided again. 

 

<p>Now, what really causes a train to be delayed? The announcer might tell you it's because of a signal fault; the staff might not tell you anything, and Trainline won’t load because the Wi-Fi isn’t working. Well, statistics for 2020/21 suggest that fatalities, equipment failures, and train faults are the most common causes of delays. Network Rail say that ‘we do everything we can to prevent delays,’ but professional Twitter user Dave Smith believe that the trains are delayed on purpose. General trends show that the amount of delays is decreasing over the whole network, but there is still lots of work to be done. 

 

<p>Another problem that continues to plague the industry is major safety issues with entire fleets of trains. In April 2021, more than one hundred trains were taken out of service from LNER and GWR Intercity routes to Edinburgh, Cardiff, Cornwall, and the North. The class 800 ‘Hitachi’ trains were found to have cracks in their wheel sets, which could have led to a serious high-speed crash. Barely a year later, the Metropolitan line experienced the same problems with its trains, leading to heavily disrupted services for thousands of commuters. At least the trains aren’t crashing... 

 

<p>Well, on the 5th of July 2022 at 6:20am, two freights trains collided in Doncaster. Luckily, nobody was injured, however the incident has sparked an investigation into why trains are still colliding in the UK.  
 

<p>The industry boasts about its safety and punctuality, but should they really be bragging when a quarter of their trains don’t run on time, and when some trains are still going off the rails?  
	  </p>
